    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I see. So it's basically saying I'm responsible for everything that falls under that \"net.\" Are there ways I can limit that? Like, can I negotiate to make the clause more specific so I'm not catching every random expense that pops up? I just don't want to find out later that there were some sneaky little details buried in there that I wasn't prepared for.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely, you can and *should* try to limit it, especially as a freelancer. A good negotiation is often about carving out exceptions, which is much safer than just accepting the whole sprawling net. You can try to narrow the scope by adding qualifiers, making it less of a \"catch-all\" and more of a targeted defense.\n\nFor instance, you could try to limit the indemnification only to losses \"arising directly from your gross negligence or willful misconduct,\" rather than *any* breach. This shifts the burden away from minor oversights to actual, serious screw-ups, which is a much more reasonable expectation for a freelancer. You could also try to cap the total amount you could be liable for—a monetary ceiling.",
      "source": "target",
